          "body": "Verses 19-20 are the chapter's epistemological climax. 'Teach us what we shall say to Him; we cannot arrange our case because of darkness.' The verb 'arrange' (*arakh*) is a legal term — setting out a case in proper forensic order. Job has used it throughout the book: he has called for a mediator (9:33), demanded a hearing (13:3, 22; 23:3-5), and insisted he could present his case before God and be acquitted (23:7). Elihu dismantles the premise. Not because Job's complaint is morally illegitimate but because the plaintiff is epistemically incapable: he argues from darkness. He cannot see what God sees. He cannot understand what God administers. And verse 20 presses the point to its limit: 'Shall it be told Him that I would speak? Or should a man say that he would be swallowed up?' The implication is devastating — a man who insists on pressing his case before the Almighty runs the risk of being swallowed by the encounter. The legal posture collapses not because God is unjust but because the distance between creature and Creator makes legal symmetry impossible. This is not the end of hope; it is the end of legal pretension. The God who cannot be found (37:23) is also the God who will find Job and speak (38:1)."
