          "body": "Verses 21-24 shift from interrogation to vision. The image of the sun blazing after the wind clears the clouds (37:21) is a natural phenomenon that becomes a symbol: blinding light, impossible to look at, suddenly present after obscurity. Then — 'Out of the north comes golden splendor; around God is awesome majesty' (37:22). The north (*tsaphon*) carries theological weight in the Hebrew Bible: Psalm 48:2 locates the divine assembly on the sides of the north; Isaiah 14:13 places the heavenly throne there. Elihu's golden splendor from the north is anticipating what is about to happen in chapter 38:1 — God will speak from the whirlwind. The theophanic hints are deliberate. Verse 23 is the chapter's theological summit: 'The Almighty — we cannot find Him; He is exalted in power and He will not do violence to justice and abundant righteousness.' Three affirmations held in irreducible tension: God is inaccessible (we cannot find Him); God is omnipotent (exalted in power); God is righteous (He will not violate justice). Job has been assuming that these three attributes cannot coexist with his suffering. Elihu insists they can — and that the proof is not a logical argument but a living encounter with the God who commands lightning. The chapter ends as it began: 'Therefore men fear Him; He does not regard any who are wise of heart' (37:24). The fear that is the beginning of wisdom (Proverbs 1:7) is the only posture that survives the encounter with divine majesty."
