        "excerpt": "God thunders with His voice wondrously, doing great things which we cannot comprehend.",
        "body": "Elihu opens his climactic speech mid-experience: a thunderstorm is audibly present, and his heart is already responding with trembling (37:1). This is not incidental atmosphere. By rooting his theology in a storm currently in progress, Elihu collapses the distance between doctrine and present reality. What he is about to say about divine sovereignty is not an abstract principle — it is what is happening overhead.\n\nThe catalogue of phenomena in verses 2-12 moves from the grandest scale (lightning to the ends of the earth, v. 3) to the most intimate (every man's hand sealed, v. 7; animals returning to their dens, v. 8) and back outward again (ice from God's breath, v. 10; storm systems redirected by divine guidance, v. 12). The rhetorical effect is total: there is no natural phenomenon, however vast or local, that escapes the active command of God. The verbs carry this weight — God *lets loose*, *says*, *seals*, *causes*. These are not the passive operations of embedded physical law; they are the direct commands of a sovereign speaker.\n\nVerse 13 is the interpretive key to the whole section. The threefold purpose — 'correction, or for His world, or for lovingkindness' — establishes that divine meteorological sovereignty is morally purposive, not random power. The same instrument (a storm) may serve three different ends depending on the wisdom of the One deploying it. Job's suffering fits the same logic: the same providence that can bring correction, sustain the earth, or express *chesed* in a single rainstorm can simultaneously hold together purposes that appear contradictory to human perception. Elihu does not explain which purpose governs Job's case — but he insists that the Purposer knows.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Pala* (wondrously, v. 5; wonders, v. 16) — root meaning to be extraordinary, beyond human ability. *Chesed* (lovingkindness, v. 13) — the OT's covenant-loyalty word, Yahweh's most characteristic attribute (Exodus 34:6). Its presence here is the chapter's pastoral lifeline: the incomprehensible God is also the *chesed* God."
