        "excerpt": "Listen to this, O Job, stand and consider the wonders of God.",
        "body": "Verse 14 is a single verse that functions as the chapter's rhetorical hinge, and it deserves treatment as a movement in its own right. Elihu issues three imperatives: *listen* (*azan*), *stand* (*amad*), and *consider* (*bin*). Each carries specific force. *Azan* is the intensive form of hearing — to give ear deliberately, as a student to a teacher. *Amad* means to stop moving and hold position — the opposite of Job's persistent forward movement toward God in legal argument. *Bin* means to discern, to understand through careful attention — the root of wisdom-literature discernment.\n\nThat these three commands are addressed to 'O Job' by name is the chapter's most direct pastoral moment. Elihu has been speaking in the third person about God (vv. 2-13); now he turns the pronoun and the posture directly onto the man. Job is not being silenced out of contempt. He is being invited into the posture that makes genuine encounter with God possible: the stopped, listening, discerning creature before an overwhelming display of divine work. Howard Hendricks observed that the greatest obstacle to Bible study is the unwillingness to be still — to let the text speak before the reader begins to interpret. Elihu's three imperatives are structurally the same invitation.\n\nThe object of the three imperatives is 'the wonders of God' (*niphle'ot El*) — not a lecture, not a proposition, but wonders. Job is being asked to attend to something he cannot control, comprehend, or argue against. The verse is therefore a compressed theology of receptivity: before God speaks from the whirlwind, the human posture must be standing still.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Azan* — literally to give ear, to open the ear organ toward the speaker. *Amad* — to stand, stand firm, take a position; here it means halt, stop moving. *Bin* — to discern, to separate out meanings; the root of *binah* (understanding), one of wisdom literature's premier cognitive virtues."
