        "excerpt": "Do you know how God establishes them, and makes the lightning of His cloud to shine?",
        "body": "Elihu's seven questions (vv. 15-20) are not a cruel taunt but a forensic demonstration. Job has sustained his legal posture for thirty-one chapters — demanding an audience with God, insisting he could present his case, and arguing that divine injustice explains his suffering. Elihu's strategy is to test the plaintiff's competence on a simpler domain before the bar. If Job cannot answer questions about floating clouds, hot garments, and the bronze firmament, what standing does he have to cross-examine the Maker of those phenomena about the moral governance of the universe?\n\nThe questions escalate from meteorological (how does God direct lightning, vv. 15-16?) to physical (why do your garments grow hot in the south wind, v. 17?) to cosmological (can you spread the sky like hammered bronze, v. 18?). The intimacy of verse 17 — 'you whose garments are hot' — is pointed: Elihu catches Job in a bodily experience happening right now that Job cannot explain. The south wind that stills the land and heats garments is as fully under divine command as the thunderstorm above. Job's own body temperature is governed by the same God whose justice he is contesting.\n\nVerses 19-20 complete the demolition. 'Teach us what we shall say to Him; we cannot arrange our case because of darkness.' The legal vocabulary (*arakh*, to arrange a case) is precise — this is the forensic term Job himself used when imagining his day in court (Job 23:4). Elihu turns it back: we cannot arrange the case because we argue from darkness, not from knowledge. And verse 20 adds the final warning: a man who presses his case before the Almighty risks being swallowed up. Douglas Moo, commenting on analogous New Testament passages about human wisdom before God, notes that the consistent biblical pattern is not that God refuses to hear human complaint but that the creature who would present a legal case must first reckon with the cognitive asymmetry that makes legal symmetry impossible.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Arakh* (arrange a case, v. 19) — legal term for setting out evidence in orderly fashion; same root used in Job 23:4, 'I would present my case before Him.' *Bala* (swallowed up, v. 20) — to engulf, devour; used of the earth swallowing Korah (Numbers 16:32) and of death swallowing up life. The threat is not metaphorical."
