        "body": "The chapter's final movement shifts from interrogation to vision. The image of verse 21 — men unable to look at the blazing sun after the wind clears the clouds — is a transitional metaphor. The physical phenomenon (blinding solar light suddenly revealed) becomes the symbol for what is approaching: divine majesty in its concentrated, unapproachable form. The wind that clears the clouds and the light that blinds the eye are the natural world's announcement of theophanic arrival.\n\nVerse 22 names the direction: 'Out of the north comes golden splendor.' The north (*tsaphon*) is theologically loaded in the Hebrew scriptures. Psalm 48:2 places God's holy mountain 'in the far north'; Isaiah 14:13 locates the divine assembly there. Elihu's choice of *tsaphon* is not meteorological precision (though north winds do bring cold, v. 9) but theological anticipation: the golden splendor from the north is the herald of the whirlwind theophany that will arrive in Job 38:1. Elihu knows something is coming. His speech is preparing the space for it.\n\nVerse 23 is the chapter's theological summit, holding three attributes in irreducible tension. The Almighty (*Shaddai*) cannot be found — He is radically transcendent. He is exalted in power — He is radically omnipotent. And He 'will not do violence to justice and abundant righteousness' — He is radically moral. Job's crisis throughout the book has been the assumed incompatibility of these three: if God is transcendent and omnipotent, how can He be just in letting the innocent suffer? Elihu does not solve the logical problem. He refuses to. Instead he insists that all three attributes are simultaneously, permanently, and uncompromisedly true — and that the God who holds them together is the One who is about to speak. Spurgeon observed that the faith which waits for God to reveal His own reasons is stronger, not weaker, than the faith that demands explanation first.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaddai* (Almighty, v. 23) — appears 31 times in Job, more than anywhere else in the OT. Its root is debated (El Shaddai = God of the mountain? God of the breast? God who is sufficient?), but its consistent usage in Job is as the name for overwhelming, sovereign divine power. *Tsedaqah* (righteousness) and *mishpat* (justice) — the two terms appear together throughout the Psalms and Prophets as the paired attributes of divine governance (Psalm 97:2; Isaiah 9:7; Amos 5:24)."
