        "excerpt": "Therefore men fear Him; He does not regard any who are wise of heart.",
        "body": "The chapter's final verse is a *therefore* — the logical and rhetorical conclusion of everything from verse 1 onward. The inferential particle *ken* (therefore) carries the full weight of the chapter's argument: God commands the storm (vv. 1-13); Job cannot answer its mechanics (vv. 14-20); God approaches in blinding, inaccessible majesty with power and righteousness inseparably joined (vv. 21-23). Therefore: fear. The conclusion is not mood; it is logic.\n\nThe fear (*yare*) Elihu commands is the same word used for the awesome majesty surrounding God in verse 22. What God IS generates what creatures must DO. This is the book of Proverbs' foundational axiom ('the fear of the LORD is the beginning of wisdom,' Proverbs 1:7) applied forensically to Job's situation: before Job can receive wisdom about his suffering, he must first occupy the posture that wisdom requires. He cannot receive what he has been demanding — an explanation — because demanding is the opposite of fearing. Jonathan Edwards observed that self-will before God is the precise antithesis of reverence, and that the soul which insists on its own terms forfeits the encounter it is demanding.\n\nThe final clause is the chapter's sharpest cut: 'He does not regard any who are wise of heart.' *Wise of heart* (*chakham lev*) sounds like a commendation. In context it is a condemnation: those whose confidence in their own discernment makes them incapable of trembling, standing still, and fearing. Job is 'wise of heart' in the worst sense — he has been prosecuting his case with moral confidence and rhetorical skill for thirty chapters. Elihu's closing word is that God does not *regard* (*raah*, see, look upon with favor) such wisdom. The only thing God looks upon with favor is the fear that emerges from the collapse of self-sufficient argument. This sets the stage perfectly for 40:4-5, where Job finally says: 'I am insignificant; what can I reply to You? I lay my hand on my mouth.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Ken* (therefore, v. 24) — inferential particle establishing logical consequence. *Yare* appears twice: as 'awesome' (v. 22) and 'fear' (v. 24) — the same root binds God's character to the creature's required response. *Chakham lev* (wise of heart) — in Proverbs this phrase is consistently positive (Proverbs 11:29; 16:21); Elihu inverts it here as a warning about wisdom that has become self-reliance."
